<br>
So I tried to help this kid out.  I devised a plan where he could get rid of this fear.  I first got him all worked up, using hypothetical situations that usually started out like, &quot;Say you're on a date with this awesome chick.&quot;, then I told him.<br>
<br>
First, get some of those little finger prickers they use to get some blood for blood typing.  Then find a nice warm cozy place like your own bed, somewhere where you feel completely safe.  Prick your finger, look at it, rinse repeat until the fear is gone.<br>
<br>
Perfect! Made complete sense to me.  I certainly believed that any resonable person would take this advice.<br>
<br>
Well, he didn't.  In fact he rejected it severly to the point of threatening me. Extremely defensive as if I was trying to steal from him.  I didn't get it at all, I couldn't understand why someone with such a huge problem wouldn't want to get rid of that problem.<br>
<br>
My guess is that his problem is extreme and deeply rooted, I can't just call him a wimp and get away with it.  It would probably take a pro psych to get him solved.  But what did escape me, was his association with it.  The phobia was like a part of him and he didn't want to get rid of it anymore than he wanted to cut a limb off.<br>
<br>
I guess I'm wondering, have you guys ever tried to get rid of these fears?  Like..  buying a bunch of cotton balls and just playing with them until you feel better about them?<br>
<br>
